featured_reviews.review_id:
Qutbul-Aqtaab Khawaja Meer Sayyid Abd al-Waheed Bilgraami al-Chisti

Referred to as the leader of the Syeds of Bilgraam, he is the forefather of the Shaykh of our Shaykhs, the Qutb, the Ghaus, Syed Shah Barakatullah of Mahrerah Shareef. He was born in 912 or 915 hijri in Saandi, a small village in the district of Awadh in North India. A Zaydi Sayyid (one who traces himself to Imam Zayd Shaheed, the son of Imam Zainul Abideen the son of Imam Hussayn [Allah be pleased with them]),

So humble was he, that when he received the robe of kilafat from his Shaykh, he did not initiate any as his disciple. Upon hearing of this, his Shaykh instructed him with the following words, "Your sole aim is to increase the number of your spiritual brethren so that some graceful person in the court of Allah may become the source of our own salvation. " He wrote the famous manuscript on Sufi Mysticism called 'Sanaa Sanaabil'. A work so accepted and acknowledged by all Sufis, that the great sufi scholar Saint of India, Aala Hadrat, Imam Ahmad Raza Al Bareillwi referring to the Sayyid on many occasions as his master also made extensive reference to this esteemed book.

The great Imam writes of him, "Sayyiduna Meer Abdul Waheed al-Hussayni al-Zaydi al-Waasti al-Bilgraami, the leader of the Sayyids of Bilgraam is the author of the prophetically accepted manuscript, 'Sanaa Sanaabil Shareef'. Being the grandfather of the respected personality who has posed these queries, he is also the master of this faqeer (Ala Hadrat). Sayyid Sha Hamzah Mahrerwi writes at the beginning of his blessed work, 'Kaashiful-Astaar':

It is known that Hadrat Sayyid Meer Abdul Wahid al-Bilgraami is an eminent and blessed personality of our family. The Qutb (axis) of the sky of salvation, the centre of the circle of Wilaayah (sainthood), he is a scholar par excellence of the manifest and the hidden branches of knowledge who has well understood the discipline of the science of research. This faqeer's (Sayyid Shah Hamzah) genealogical chain reaches him by four generations.

He continues after a few other sentences,

'Sanaabil' is his renowned opus on the subjects of Sulook and Aqaaid. Sayyid Ghulaam Ali Azaad writes in the book, 'Manatharul Kalaam':

'It was during the Ramadan of the year 1135 A. H.that I presented myself in the court of Shah Kaleemullah al-Chisti. Sayyid Meer Abdul Waheed was made mention of in our dialogue. The respected Shaykh spoke on the distinction of the excellence of Meer Abdul Waheed for a lengthy cycle. Said he, ' during a night in Madina al-Munnawarra, I saw in a dream, Sayyid Sibyaatullah and myself present in the court of the Prophet of Allah (peace and blessings of Allah be upon him). Also present in the holy court were a group of Sahabah and Awliya. There was an individual in this gathering who had the Prophet of Allah (peace and blessings of Allah be upon him) constantly looking in his direction, smiling at him and conversing with him. The complete special attention of the Prophet of Allah (peace and blessings of Allah be upon him) was focused on him.

Upon the termination of this gathering, I enquired as to the identity of this individual from Sayyid Sibyaatullah. He replied that it was Meer Abdul Waheed and explained that he was being honoured by the Prophet of Allah (peace and blessings of Allah be upon him) to that extent because of having penned the book 'Sanaabil', a book that had been accepted in the prophetic court. ' (Kaashiful-Astaar, Pg 41; Asahut-Tawaareekh, Vol 1, Pg 168; Maa an tharul-Kalaam, Pg 29) "

His life spanned more than a century, witnessing nine to ten of the Moghul Emperors. So great was the Moghul Ruler, Akbar s, respect for him that when he wanted to meet the great Sayyid, he had him seated side by side, to his own throne in his court. The Sayyid journeyed to the hereafter on the 30th of Ramadan 1017 Hijri and lies buried in his hometown in Bilgraam.
